pr_body:
Use an url to download a file.

So the syntax changes to:
`FileSaver saveAs(Blob/File/URL data, optional DOMString filename, optional Boolean disableAutoBOM)`

E.G.
saveAs('pathToFile/something.csv');

--
P.S. Used this extenstion to provide support for IE10/IE11 for the [download](http://caniuse.com/#feat=download) argument in a link:
```javascript
if (!Modernizr.adownload) {
  $('a[download]').on('click', function() {
    var href = $(this).attr('href'),
        splitHref = href.split('/'),
        name = splitHref[splitHref.length-1];
   
    saveAs(href, name);
    return false;
  });
}
```

The proposed PR removes template arguments from the class name in the member function. Otherwise links to nested classes (in parameter or return types) defined in the same template are not generated correctly, because the latter don't include template arguments.

For example, `void C<T>::f(D)` is converted to `void C::f(D)` in

```c++
/** A class */
template <typename T>
class C {
 public:
  /** An inner class. */
  class D {};

  /** A method. */
  void f(D);
};
```

Fixes #179.

@michaeljones, if you merged #189 first, I could also add a unit test for this.

@kevinhughes27 for review

Porting https://github.com/Shopify/shopify_api/pull/188 to python.

I ended up using str.replace to escape the same subset of characters, and to make sure the case of the URI escape codes is the same.
